//wap in java for electeic car 
/*step 1: create an interface with abstract methods
step 2: create a class that implements the interface and provides implementation for the abstract methods
step 3: create an object of the class and call the methods to demonstrate abstraction using interface
step 4: run the program to see how abstraction works using interface in java.
step 5: compare abstraction using abstract class and interface to understand the differences and use cases for each.
step 6: understand that abstract class is used when we want to provide a common base for subclasses and enforce a certain structure, while interface is used when we want to define a contract that classes can implement regardless of their position in the class hierarchy.
 */
class car{
    public void start(){
        System.out.println("Car is starting ....");
    }
    public void stop(){
        System.out.println("Car is stopping ....");
    }
}
interface ElectricVehicle{
    void charge();
    void displayBatteryLevel();
}
class ElectricCar implements ElectricVehicle{
    public void charge(){
        System.out.println("Electric car is charging ....");
    }
    public void displayBatteryLevel(){
        System.out.println("Battery level is 80% ....");
    }
}


